# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: subsurface-scattering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:subsurface-scattering/bidirectional-scattering-distribution-function] The definition of the **bidirectional scattering distribution function** (**BSDF**) is not well standardized.
[src:subsurface-scattering/bidirectional-scattering-distribution-function] The term was probably introduced in 1980 by Bartell, Dereniak, and Wolfe.
[src:subsurface-scattering/bidirectional-scattering-distribution-function] Most often it is used to name the general mathematical function which describes the way in which the light is scattered by a surface.
[src:subsurface-scattering/bidirectional-scattering-distribution-function] However, in practice, this phenomenon is usually split into the reflected and transmitted components, which are then treated separately as the **bidirectional reflectance distribution function** (**BRDF**) and **bidirectional transmittance distribution function** (**BTDF**) respectively.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] The fundamental quantity that describes a field of radiation is called **spectral radiance** in radiometric terms (in other fields it is often called **specific intensity**).
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] For a very small area element in the radiation field, there can be electromagnetic radiation passing in both senses in every spatial direction through it.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] where $\theta$ is the angle that the unit direction vector ${\hat {\mathbf {n} }}$ makes with a normal to the area element.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] The units of the spectral radiance are seen to be energy/time/area/solid angle/frequency.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] In MKS units this would be W·m−2·sr−1·Hz−1 (watts per square-metre-steradian-hertz).
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] The equation of radiative transfer simply says that as a beam of radiation travels, it loses energy to absorption, gains energy by emission processes, and redistributes energy by scattering.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] Solutions to the equation of radiative transfer form an enormous body of work.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] The differences however, are essentially due to the various forms for the emission and absorption coefficients.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] A particularly useful simplification of the equation of radiative transfer occurs under the conditions of local thermodynamic equilibrium (LTE).
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] Local equilibrium may apply only to a certain subset of particles in the system.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] For example, LTE is usually applied only to massive particles.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] In a radiating gas, the photons being emitted and absorbed by the gas do not need to be in a thermodynamic equilibrium with each other or with the massive particles of the gas in order for LTE to exist.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] In this situation, the absorbing/emitting medium consists of massive particles which are locally in equilibrium with each other, and therefore have a definable temperature (Zeroth Law of Thermodynamics).
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] The radiation field is not, however in equilibrium and is being entirely driven by the presence of the massive particles.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] where $B_{\nu }(T)$ is the black body spectral radiance at temperature T.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] Knowing the temperature profile and the density profile of the medium is sufficient to calculate a solution to the equation of radiative transfer.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] The Eddington approximation is distinct from the two-stream approximation.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] The two-stream approximation assumes that the intensity is constant with angle in the upward hemisphere, with a different constant value in the downward hemisphere.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] $I_{\nu }(\mu ,z)=a(z)+\mu b(z)$ where z is the normal direction to the slab-like medium.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] Note that expressing angular integrals in terms of $\mu$ simplifies things because $d\mu =-\sin \theta \,d\theta$ appears in the Jacobian of integrals in spherical coordinates.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] The Eddington approximation can be used to obtain the spectral radiance in a "plane-parallel" medium (one in which properties only vary in the perpendicular direction) with isotropic frequency-independent scattering.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] Thus the Eddington approximation is equivalent to setting ${\textstyle K_{\nu }={\frac {1}{3}}J_{\nu }}$ .
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] Higher order versions of the Eddington approximation also exist, and consist of more complicated linear relations of the intensity moments.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] This extra equation can be used as a closure relation for the truncated system of moments.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] Note that the first two moments have simple physical meanings. $J_{\nu }$ is the isotropic intensity at a point, and $H_{\nu }$ is the flux through that point in the z direction.
[src:subsurface-scattering/radiative-transfer] This equation shows how the effective optical depth in scattering-dominated systems may be significantly different from that given by the scattering opacity if the absorptive opacity is small.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] In physics, **refraction** is the redirection of a wave as it passes from one medium to another.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] The redirection can be caused by the wave's change in speed or by a change in the medium.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Refraction of light is the most commonly observed phenomenon, but other waves such as sound waves and water waves also experience refraction.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] How much a wave is refracted is determined by the change in wave speed and the initial direction of wave propagation relative to the direction of change in speed.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Optical prisms and lenses use refraction to redirect light, as does the human eye.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] The refractive index of materials varies with the wavelength of light, and thus the angle of the refraction also varies correspondingly.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] This is called dispersion and allows certain prisms and raindrops in rainbows to divide white light into its constituent spectral colors.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Refraction involves two related parts, both a result of the wave nature of light: a reduced speed in an optical medium and a change in angle when a wave front crosses between different media at an angle.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] When light enters a slower medium at an angle, one side of the wavefront is slowed before the other.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] This asymmetrical slowing of the light causes it to change the angle of its travel.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Once light is within the new medium with constant properties, it travels in a straight line again.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] As described above, the speed of light is slower in a medium other than vacuum.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] This slowing applies to any medium such as air, water, or glass, and is responsible for phenomena such as refraction.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] On the other side of the medium its speed will again be the speed of light in vacuum, c.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] A correct explanation rests on light's nature as an electromagnetic wave.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Because light is an oscillating electrical/magnetic wave, light traveling in a medium causes the electrically charged electrons of the material to also oscillate.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] (The material's protons also oscillate but as they are around 2000 times more massive, their movement and therefore their effect, is far smaller).
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] A moving electrical charge emits electromagnetic waves of its own.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] The electromagnetic waves emitted by the oscillating electrons interact with the electromagnetic waves that make up the original light, similar to water waves on a pond, a process known as constructive interference.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] When two waves interfere in this way, the resulting "combined" wave may have wave packets that pass an observer at a slower rate.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] When the light leaves the material, this interaction with electrons no longer happens, and therefore the wave packet rate (and therefore its speed) return to normal.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Consider a wave going from one material to another where its speed is slower as in the figure.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] If it reaches the interface between the materials at an angle one side of the wave will reach the second material first, and therefore slow down earlier.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] With one side of the wave going slower the whole wave will pivot towards that side.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] This is why a wave will bend away from the surface or toward the normal when going into a slower material.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] In the opposite case of a wave reaching a material where the speed is higher, one side of the wave will speed up and the wave will pivot away from that side.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Another way of understanding the same thing is to consider the change in wavelength at the interface.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] When the wave goes from one material to another where the wave has a different speed v, the frequency f of the wave will stay the same, but the distance between wavefronts or wavelength *λ* = *v*/*f* will change.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] If the speed is decreased, such as in the figure to the right, the wavelength will also decrease.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] With an angle between the wave fronts and the interface and change in distance between the wave fronts the angle must change over the interface to keep the wave fronts intact.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] From these considerations the relationship between the angle of incidence *θ*1, angle of transmission *θ*2 and the wave speeds *v*1 and *v*2 in the two materials can be derived.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] The phenomenon of refraction can in a more fundamental way be derived from the 2 or 3-dimensional wave equation.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] The boundary condition at the interface will then require the tangential component of the wave vector to be identical on the two sides of the interface.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Since the magnitude of the wave vector depend on the wave speed this requires a change in direction of the wave vector.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] The relevant wave speed in the discussion above is the phase velocity of the wave.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] This is typically close to the group velocity which can be seen as the truer speed of a wave, but when they differ it is important to use the phase velocity in all calculations relating to refraction.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] A wave traveling perpendicular to a boundary, i.e. having its wavefronts parallel to the boundary, will not change direction even if the speed of the wave changes.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Refraction is also responsible for rainbows and for the splitting of white light into a rainbow-spectrum as it passes through a glass prism.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Glass and water have higher refractive indexes than air.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] The different colors correspond to different frequencies and different wavelengths.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Refraction occurs when light goes through a water surface since water has a refractive index of 1.33 and air has a refractive index of about 1.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Looking at a straight object, such as a pencil in the figure here, which is placed at a slant, partially in the water, the object appears to bend at the water's surface.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] This is due to the bending of light rays as they move from the water to the air.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Once the rays reach the eye, the eye traces them back as straight lines (lines of sight).
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] The lines of sight (shown as dashed lines) intersect at a higher position than where the actual rays originated.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] This causes the pencil to appear higher and the water to appear shallower than it really is.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] The depth that the water appears to be when viewed from above is known as the *apparent depth*.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] This is an important consideration for spearfishing from the surface because it will make the target fish appear to be in a different place, and the fisher must aim lower to catch the fish.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Conversely, an object above the water has a higher *apparent height* when viewed from below the water.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] The opposite correction must be made by an archer fish.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] For small angles of incidence (measured from the normal, when sin *θ* is approximately the same as tan *θ*), the ratio of apparent to real depth is the ratio of the refractive indexes of air to that of water.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] But, as the angle of incidence approaches 90°, the apparent depth approaches zero, albeit reflection increases, which limits observation at high angles of incidence.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Conversely, the apparent height approaches infinity as the angle of incidence (from below) increases, but even earlier, as the angle of total internal reflection is approached, albeit the image also fades from view as this limit is approached.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] The refractive index of air depends on the air density and thus vary with air temperature and pressure.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Since the pressure is lower at higher altitudes, the refractive index is also lower, causing light rays to refract towards the earth surface when traveling long distances through the atmosphere.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] This shifts the apparent positions of stars slightly when they are close to the horizon and makes the sun visible before it geometrically rises above the horizon during a sunrise.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Temperature variations in the air can also cause refraction of light.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] This can be seen as a heat haze when hot and cold air is mixed e.g. over a fire, in engine exhaust, or when opening a window on a cold day.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] This makes objects viewed through the mixed air appear to shimmer or move around randomly as the hot and cold air moves.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] This effect is also visible from normal variations in air temperature during a sunny day when using high magnification telephoto lenses and is often limiting the image quality in these cases.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] In a similar way, atmospheric turbulence gives rapidly varying distortions in the images of astronomical telescopes limiting the resolution of terrestrial telescopes not using adaptive optics or other techniques for overcoming these atmospheric distortions.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Air temperature variations close to the surface can give rise to other optical phenomena, such as mirages and Fata Morgana.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Most commonly, air heated by a hot road on a sunny day deflects light approaching at a shallow angle towards a viewer.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] This makes the road appear reflecting, giving an illusion of water covering the road.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] In medicine, particularly optometry, ophthalmology and orthoptics, *refraction* (also known as *refractometry*) is a clinical test in which a phoropter may be used by the appropriate eye care professional to determine the eye's refractive error and the best corrective lenses to be prescribed.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] A series of test lenses in graded optical powers or focal lengths are presented to determine which provides the sharpest, clearest vision.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Refractive surgery is a medical procedure to treat common vision disorders.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Water waves travel slower in shallower water.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] This can be used to demonstrate refraction in ripple tanks and also explains why waves on a shoreline tend to strike the shore close to a perpendicular angle.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] As the waves travel from deep water into shallower water near the shore, they are refracted from their original direction of travel to an angle more normal to the shoreline.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] In underwater acoustics, refraction is the bending or curving of a sound ray that results when the ray passes through a sound speed gradient from a region of one sound speed to a region of a different speed.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] The amount of ray bending is dependent on the amount of difference between sound speeds, that is, the variation in temperature, salinity, and pressure of the water.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Similar acoustics effects are also found in the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] The phenomenon of refraction of sound in the atmosphere has been known for centuries.
[src:subsurface-scattering/refraction] Beginning in the early 1970s, widespread analysis of this effect came into vogue through the designing of urban highways and noise barriers to address the meteorological effects of bending of sound rays in the lower atmosphere.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Other animal coverings, such as the arthropod exoskeleton, have different developmental origin, structure and chemical composition.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The adjective **cutaneous** means "of the skin" (from Latin *cutis* 'skin').
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] In mammals, the skin is an organ of the integumentary system made up of multiple layers of ectodermal tissue and guards the underlying muscles, bones, ligaments, and internal organs.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Skin of a different nature exists in amphibians, reptiles, and birds.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Skin (including cutaneous and subcutaneous tissues) plays crucial roles in formation, structure, and function of extraskeletal apparatus such as horns of bovids (e.g., cattle) and rhinos, cervids' antlers, giraffids' ossicones, armadillos' osteoderm, and os penis/os clitoris.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] All mammals have some hair on their skin, even marine mammals like whales, dolphins, and porpoises that appear to be hairless.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The skin interfaces with the environment and is the first line of defense from external factors.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] For example, the skin plays a key role in protecting the body against pathogens and excessive water loss.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Its other functions are insulation, temperature regulation, sensation, and the production of vitamin D folates.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Severely damaged skin may heal by forming scar tissue.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] This is sometimes discoloured and depigmented.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The thickness of skin also varies from location to location on an organism.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] In humans, for example, the skin located under the eyes and around the eyelids is the thinnest skin on the body at 0.5 mm thick and is one of the first areas to show signs of aging such as "crows feet" and wrinkles.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The skin on the palms and the soles of the feet is the thickest skin on the body at 4 mm thick.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The speed and quality of wound healing in skin is promoted by estrogen.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Primarily, fur augments the insulation the skin provides but can also serve as a secondary sexual characteristic or as camouflage.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] On some animals, the skin is very hard and thick and can be processed to create leather.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Reptiles and most fish have hard protective scales on their skin for protection, and birds have hard feathers, all made of tough beta-keratins.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Amphibian skin is not a strong barrier, especially regarding the passage of chemicals via skin, and is often subject to osmosis and diffusive forces.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] For example, a frog sitting in an anesthetic solution would be sedated quickly as the chemical diffuses through its skin.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Amphibian skin plays key roles in everyday survival and their ability to exploit a wide range of habitats and ecological conditions.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] On 11 January 2024, biologists reported the discovery of the oldest known skin, fossilized about 289 million years ago, and possibly the skin from an ancient reptile.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The word skin originally only referred to dressed and tanned animal hide and the usual word for human skin was hide.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Skin is a borrowing from Old Norse *skinn* "animal hide, fur", ultimately from the Proto-Indo-European root *sek-, meaning "to cut" (probably a reference to the fact that in those times animal hide was commonly cut off to be used as garment).
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The epidermis is composed of the outermost layers of the skin.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] It forms a protective barrier over the body's surface, responsible for keeping water in the body and preventing pathogens from entering, and is a stratified squamous epithelium, composed of proliferating basal and differentiated suprabasal keratinocytes.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Keratinocytes are the major cells, constituting 95% of the epidermis, while Merkel cells, melanocytes and Langerhans cells are also present.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Keratinocytes in the stratum basale proliferate through mitosis and the daughter cells move up the strata changing shape and composition as they undergo multiple stages of cell differentiation to eventually become anucleated.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] During that process, keratinocytes will become highly organized, forming cellular junctions (desmosomes) between each other and secreting keratin proteins and lipids which contribute to the formation of an extracellular matrix and provide mechanical strength to the skin.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Keratinocytes from the stratum corneum are eventually shed from the surface (desquamation).
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The epidermis contains no blood vessels, and cells in the deepest layers are nourished by diffusion from blood capillaries extending to the upper layers of the dermis.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The epidermis and dermis are separated by a thin sheet of fibers called the basement membrane, which is made through the action of both tissues.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The basement membrane controls the traffic of the cells and molecules between the dermis and epidermis but also serves, through the binding of a variety of cytokines and growth factors, as a reservoir for their controlled release during physiological remodeling or repair processes.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The **dermis** is the layer of skin beneath the epidermis that consists of connective tissue and cushions the body from stress and strain.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The dermis provides tensile strength and elasticity to the skin through an extracellular matrix composed of collagen fibrils, microfibrils, and elastic fibers, embedded in hyaluronan and proteoglycans.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Skin proteoglycans are varied and have very specific locations.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] For example, hyaluronan, versican and decorin are present throughout the dermis and epidermis extracellular matrix, whereas biglycan and perlecan are only found in the epidermis.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] It harbors many mechanoreceptors (nerve endings) that provide the sense of touch and heat through nociceptors and thermoreceptors.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] It also contains the hair follicles, sweat glands, sebaceous glands, apocrine glands, lymphatic vessels and blood vessels.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The blood vessels in the dermis provide nourishment and waste removal from its own cells as well as for the epidermis.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Dermis and subcutaneous tissues are thought to contain germinative cells involved in formation of horns, osteoderm, and other extra-skeletal apparatus in mammals.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The dermis is tightly connected to the epidermis through a basement membrane and is structurally divided into two areas: a superficial area adjacent to the epidermis, called the *papillary region*, and a deep thicker area known as the *reticular region*.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The papillary region is composed of loose areolar connective tissue.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] This is named for its fingerlike projections called *papillae* that extend toward the epidermis.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The papillae provide the dermis with a "bumpy" surface that interdigitates with the epidermis, strengthening the connection between the two layers of skin.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The reticular region lies deep in the papillary region and is usually much thicker.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] It is composed of dense irregular connective tissue and receives its name from the dense concentration of collagenous, elastic, and reticular fibers that weave throughout it.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] These protein fibers give the dermis its properties of strength, extensibility, and elasticity.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Also located within the reticular region are the roots of the hair, sweat glands, sebaceous glands, receptors, nails, and blood vessels.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The subcutaneous tissue (also hypodermis) is not part of the skin, and lies below the dermis.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Its purpose is to attach the skin to underlying bone and muscle as well as supplying it with blood vessels and nerves.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] It consists of loose connective tissue and elastin.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The main cell types are fibroblasts, macrophages and adipocytes (the subcutaneous tissue contains 50% of body fat).
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Fat serves as padding and insulation for the body.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Microorganisms like *Staphylococcus epidermidis* colonize the skin surface.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The density of skin flora depends on region of the skin.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The disinfected skin surface gets recolonized from bacteria residing in the deeper areas of the hair follicle, gut and urogenital openings.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The epidermis of fish and of most amphibians consists entirely of live cells, with only minimal quantities of keratin in the cells of the superficial layer.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] It is generally permeable, and in the case of many amphibians, may actually be a major respiratory organ.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The dermis of bony fish typically contains relatively little of the connective tissue found in tetrapods.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Instead, in most species, it is largely replaced by solid, protective bony scales.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Apart from some particularly large dermal bones that form parts of the skull, these scales are lost in tetrapods, although many reptiles do have scales of a different kind, as do pangolins.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Cartilaginous fish have numerous tooth-like denticles embedded in their skin, in place of true scales.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Sweat glands and sebaceous glands are both unique to mammals, but other types of skin gland are found in other vertebrates.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Fish typically have a numerous individual mucus-secreting skin cells that aid in insulation and protection, but may also have poison glands, photophores, or cells that produce a more watery, serous fluid.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] In amphibians, the mucous cells are gathered together to form sac-like glands.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Most living amphibians also possess *granular glands* in the skin, that secrete irritating or toxic compounds.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Although melanin is found in the skin of many species, in the reptiles, the amphibians, and fish, the epidermis is often relatively colorless.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Instead, the color of the skin is largely due to chromatophores in the dermis, which, in addition to melanin, may contain guanine or carotenoid pigments.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Many species, such as chameleons and flounders may be able to change the color of their skin by adjusting the relative size of their chromatophores.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Amphibians possess two types of glands, mucous and granular (serous).
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Both of these glands are part of the integument and thus considered cutaneous.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Mucous and granular glands are both divided into three different sections which all connect to structure the gland as a whole.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The three individual parts of the gland are the duct, the intercalary region, and lastly the alveolar gland (sac).
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Structurally, the duct is derived via keratinocytes and passes through to the surface of the epidermal or outer skin layer thus allowing external secretions of the body.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The gland alveolus is a sac-shaped structure that is found on the bottom or base region of the granular gland.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The cells in this sac specialize in secretion.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Between the alveolar gland and the duct is the intercalary system which can be summed up as a transitional region connecting the duct to the grand alveolar beneath the epidermal skin layer.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] In general, granular glands are larger in size than the mucous glands, which are greater in number.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Granular glands can be identified as venomous and often differ in the type of toxin as well as the concentrations of secretions across various orders and species within the amphibians.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] They are located in clusters differing in concentration depending on amphibian taxa.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The toxins can be fatal to most vertebrates or have no effect against others.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] These glands are alveolar meaning they structurally have little sacs in which venom is produced and held before it is secreted upon defensive behaviors.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Structurally, the ducts of the granular gland initially maintain a cylindrical shape.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] When the ducts mature and fill with fluid, the base of the ducts become swollen due to the pressure from the inside.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] This causes the epidermal layer to form a pit like opening on the surface of the duct in which the inner fluid will be secreted in an upwards fashion.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The intercalary region of granular glands is more developed and mature in comparison with mucous glands.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] This region resides as a ring of cells surrounding the basal portion of the duct which are argued to have an ectodermal muscular nature due to their influence over the lumen (space inside the tube) of the duct with dilation and constriction functions during secretions.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The cells are found radially around the duct and provide a distinct attachment site for muscle fibers around the gland's body.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The gland alveolus is a sac that is divided into three specific regions/layers.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The outer layer or tunica fibrosa is composed of densely packed connective-tissue which connects with fibers from the spongy intermediate layer where elastic fibers, as well as nerves, reside.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The nerves send signals to the muscles as well as the epithelial layers.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Lastly, the epithelium or tunica propria encloses the gland.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Mucous glands are non-venomous and offer a different functionality for amphibians than granular.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Mucous glands cover the entire surface area of the amphibian body and specialize in keeping the body lubricated.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] There are many other functions of the mucous glands such as controlling the pH, thermoregulation, adhesive properties to the environment, anti-predator behaviors (slimy to the grasp), chemical communication, even anti-bacterial/viral properties for protection against pathogens.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The ducts of the mucous gland appear as cylindrical vertical tubes that break through the epidermal layer to the surface of the skin.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The cells lining the inside of the ducts are oriented with their longitudinal axis forming 90-degree angles surrounding the duct in a helical fashion.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Intercalary cells react identically to those of granular glands but on a smaller scale.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Among the amphibians, there are taxa which contain a modified intercalary region (depending on the function of the glands), yet the majority share the same structure.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The alveolar or mucous glands are much more simple and only consist of an epithelium layer as well as connective tissue which forms a cover over the gland.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] This gland lacks a tunica propria and appears to have delicate and intricate fibers which pass over the gland's muscle and epithelial layers.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The epidermis of birds and reptiles is closer to that of mammals, with a layer of dead keratin-filled cells at the surface, to help reduce water loss.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] A similar pattern is also seen in some of the more terrestrial amphibians such as toads.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] In these animals, there is no clear differentiation of the epidermis into distinct layers initially, as occurs in humans, with the change in cell type being relatively gradual.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The mammalian epidermis always possesses at least a stratum germinativum and stratum corneum, but the other intermediate layers found in humans are not always distinguishable.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Hair is a distinctive feature of mammalian skin, while feathers are (at least among living species) similarly unique to birds.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Birds and reptiles have relatively few skin glands, although there may be a few structures for specific purposes, such as pheromone-secreting cells in some reptiles, or the uropygial gland of most birds.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Cutaneous structures arise from the epidermis and include a variety of features such as hair, feathers, claws and nails.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] During embryogenesis, the epidermis splits into two layers: the periderm (which is lost) and the basal layer.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The basal layer is a stem cell layer and through asymmetrical divisions, becomes the source of skin cells throughout life.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] It is maintained as a stem cell layer through an autocrine signal, TGF alpha, and through paracrine signaling from FGF7 (keratinocyte growth factor) produced by the dermis below the basal cells.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] In mice, over-expression of these factors leads to an overproduction of granular cells and thick skin.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Hair and feathers are formed in a regular pattern and it is believed to be the result of a reaction-diffusion system.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] This reaction-diffusion system combines an activator, Sonic hedgehog, with an inhibitor, BMP4 or BMP2, to form clusters of cells in a regular pattern.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Sonic hedgehog-expressing epidermal cells induce the condensation of cells in the mesoderm.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The clusters of mesodermal cells signal back to the epidermis to form the appropriate structure for that position.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] BMP signals from the epidermis inhibit the formation of placodes in nearby ectoderm.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] It is believed that the mesoderm defines the pattern.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The epidermis instructs the mesodermal cells to condense and then the mesoderm instructs the epidermis of what structure to make through a series of reciprocal inductions.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Sensation: contains a variety of nerve endings that jump to heat and cold, touch, pressure, vibration, and tissue injury (see somatosensory system and haptic perception).
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Thermoregulation: Eccrine (sweat) glands and dilated blood vessels (increased superficial perfusion) aid heat loss, while constricted vessels greatly reduce cutaneous blood flow and conserve heat.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Erector pili muscles in mammals adjust the angle of hair shafts to change the degree of insulation provided by hair or fur.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Control of evaporation: the skin provides a relatively dry and semi-impermeable barrier to reduce fluid loss.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Water resistance: The skin acts as a water resistant barrier so essential nutrients aren't washed out of the body.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The nutrients and oils that help hydrate the skin are covered by the most outer skin layer, the epidermis.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] This is helped in part by the sebaceous glands that release sebum, an oily liquid.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Water itself will not cause the elimination of oils on the skin, because the oils residing in our dermis flow and would be affected by water without the epidermis.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Camouflage, whether the skin is naked or covered in fur, scales, or feathers, skin structures provide protective coloration and patterns that help to conceal animals from predators or prey.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Skin is a soft tissue and exhibits key mechanical behaviors of these tissues.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] The most pronounced feature is the J-curve stress strain response, in which a region of large strain and minimal stress exists and corresponds to the microstructural straightening and reorientation of collagen fibrils.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] In some cases the intact skin is prestreched, like wetsuits around the diver's body, and in other cases the intact skin is under compression.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Small circular holes punched on the skin may widen or close into ellipses, or shrink and remain circular, depending on preexisting stresses.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Tissue homeostasis generally declines with age, in part because stem/progenitor cells fail to self-renew or differentiate.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Skin aging is caused in part by TGF-β by blocking the conversion of dermal fibroblasts into fat cells which provide support.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Common changes in the skin as a result of aging range from wrinkles, discoloration, and skin laxity, but can manifest in more severe forms such as skin malignancies.
[src:subsurface-scattering/skin] Moreover, these factors may be worsened by sun exposure in a process known as photoaging.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] Subsurface scattering is important for realistic 3D computer graphics, being necessary for the rendering of materials such as marble, skin, leaves, wax and milk.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] If subsurface scattering is not implemented, the material may look unnatural, like plastic or metal.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] To improve rendering efficiency, many real-time computer graphics algorithms only compute the reflectance at the surface of an object.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] In reality, many materials are slightly translucent: light enters the surface; is absorbed, scattered and re-emitted – potentially at a different point.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] Skin is a good case in point; only about 6% of reflectance is direct, 94% is from subsurface scattering.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] An inherent property of semitransparent materials is absorption.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] The further through the material light travels, the greater the proportion absorbed.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] To simulate this effect, a measure of the distance the light has traveled through the material must be obtained.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] Published by Pixar, this technique is considered the state of the art, usually integrated into a path-tracing renderer.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] It essentially simulates what happens to real photons by tracing a light path into the material, generating new paths using a lambertian distribution around the inverted normal, then picking new directions at multiple steps to scatter the light path further, hence the name "random walk".
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] Isotropic scattering is simulated by picking random directions evenly along a sphere.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] Anisotropic scattering is simulated usually by using the Henyey-Greenstein phase function.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] For example, human skin has anisotropic scattering.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] Optical depth / absorption is applied based on the length of the paths, using the Beer-Lambert law.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] Paths may be terminated inside the material when they reach a contribution minimum threshold or a maximum iteration count.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] When a path (ray) hits the surface again, it is used for gathering radiance from the scene, weighted by a lambertian distribution, as in a traditional path-tracer.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] This technique is intuitive and is robust against thin geometry.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] One method of estimating this distance is to use depth maps, in a manner similar to shadow mapping.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] The scene is rendered from the light's point of view into a depth map, so that the distance to the nearest surface is stored.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] The depth map is then projected onto it using standard projective texture mapping and the scene re-rendered.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] In this pass, when shading a given point, the distance from the light at the point the ray entered the surface can be obtained by a simple texture lookup.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] By subtracting this value from the point the ray exited the object we can gather an estimate of the distance the light has traveled through the object.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] The measure of distance obtained by this method can be used in several ways.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] One such way is to use it to index directly into an artist created 1D texture that falls off exponentially with distance.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] This approach, combined with other more traditional lighting models, allows the creation of different materials such as marble, jade and wax.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] Potentially, problems can arise if models are not convex, but depth peeling can be used to avoid the issue.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] Similarly, depth peeling can be used to account for varying densities beneath the surface, such as bone or muscle, to give a more accurate scattering model.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] As can be seen in the image of the wax head to the right, light isn't diffused when passing through object using this technique; back features are clearly shown.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] One solution to this is to take multiple samples at different points on surface of the depth map.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] Alternatively, a different approach to approximation can be used, known as texture-space diffusion.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] As noted at the start of the section, one of the more obvious effects of subsurface scattering is a general blurring of the diffuse lighting.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] Rather than arbitrarily modifying the diffuse function, diffusion can be more accurately modeled by simulating it in texture space.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] This technique was pioneered in rendering faces in *The Matrix Reloaded*, but is also used in the realm of real-time rendering techniques.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] The method unwraps the mesh of an object using a vertex shader, first calculating the lighting based on the original vertex coordinates.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] The vertices are then remapped using the UV texture coordinates as the screen position of the vertex, suitable transformed from the [0, 1] range of texture coordinates to the [-1, 1] range of normalized device coordinates.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] By lighting the unwrapped mesh in this manner, we obtain a 2D image representing the lighting on the object, which can then be processed and reapplied to the model as a light map.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] To simulate diffusion, the light map texture can simply be blurred.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] Rendering the lighting to a lower-resolution texture in itself provides a certain amount of blurring.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] The amount of blurring required to accurately model subsurface scattering in skin is still under active research, but performing only a single blur poorly models the true effects.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] To emulate the wavelength dependent nature of diffusion, the samples used during the (Gaussian) blur can be weighted by channel.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] This is somewhat of an artistic process.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] For human skin, the broadest scattering is in red, then green, and blue has very little scattering.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] A major benefit of this method is its independence of screen resolution; shading is performed only once per texel in the texture map, rather than for every pixel on the object.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] An obvious requirement is thus that the object have a good UV mapping, in that each point on the texture must map to only one point of the object.
[src:subsurface-scattering/subsurface-scattering] Additionally, the use of texture space diffusion provides one of the several factors that contribute to soft shadows, alleviating one cause of the realism deficiency of shadow mapping.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] In the field of optics, **transparency** (also called **pellucidity** or **diaphaneity**) is the physical property of allowing light to pass through the material without appreciable scattering of light.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] On a macroscopic scale (one in which the dimensions are much larger than the wavelengths of the photons in question), the photons can be said to follow Snell's law.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] **Translucency** (also called **translucence** or **translucidity**) is the physical property of allowing light to pass through the material (with or without scattering of light).
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] It allows light to pass through but the light does not necessarily follow Snell's law on the macroscopic scale; the photons may be scattered at either of the two interfaces, or internally, where there is a change in the index of refraction.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] In other words, a translucent material is made up of components with different indices of refraction, while a transparent material is made up of components with a uniform index of refraction.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Transparent materials appear clear, with the overall appearance of one color, or any combination leading up to a brilliant spectrum of every color.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The opposite property of translucency is *opacity*.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Other categories of visual appearance, related to the perception of regular or diffuse reflection and transmission of light, have been organized under the concept of cesia in an order system with three variables, including transparency, translucency and opacity among the involved aspects.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] When light encounters a material, it can interact with it in several different ways.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] These interactions depend on the wavelength of the light and the nature of the material.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Photons interact with an object by some combination of reflection, absorption and transmission.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Some materials, such as plate glass and clean water, transmit much of the light that falls on them and reflect little of it; such materials are called optically transparent.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Many liquids and aqueous solutions are highly transparent.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Absence of structural defects (voids, cracks, etc.) and molecular structure of most liquids are mostly responsible for excellent optical transmission.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Materials that do not transmit light are called opaque.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Many such substances have a chemical composition which includes what are referred to as absorption centers.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Many substances are selective in their absorption of white light frequencies.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] They absorb certain portions of the visible spectrum while reflecting others.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The frequencies of the spectrum which are not absorbed are either reflected or transmitted for our physical observation.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The attenuation of light of all frequencies and wavelengths is due to the combined mechanisms of absorption and scattering.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Transparency can provide almost perfect camouflage for animals able to achieve it.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] This is easier in dimly-lit or turbid seawater than in good illumination.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Many marine animals such as jellyfish are highly transparent.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] With regard to the scattering of light, the most critical factor is the length scale of any or all of these structural features relative to the wavelength of the light being scattered.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Diffuse reflection is typically characterized by omni-directional reflection angles.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Most of the objects visible to the naked eye are identified via diffuse reflection.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Another term commonly used for this type of reflection is "light scattering".
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Light scattering from the surfaces of objects is our primary mechanism of physical observation.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Light scattering in liquids and solids depends on the wavelength of the light being scattered.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Limits to spatial scales of visibility (using white light) therefore arise, depending on the frequency of the light wave and the physical dimension (or spatial scale) of the scattering center.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Visible light has a wavelength scale on the order of 0.5 μm.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Scattering centers (or particles) as small as 1 μm have been observed directly in the light microscope (e.g., Brownian motion).
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Optical transparency in polycrystalline materials is limited by the amount of light scattered by their microstructural features.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Light scattering depends on the wavelength of the light.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Limits to spatial scales of visibility (using white light) therefore arise, depending on the frequency of the light wave and the physical dimension of the scattering center.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] For example, since visible light has a wavelength scale on the order of a micrometre, scattering centers will have dimensions on a similar spatial scale.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Primary scattering centers in polycrystalline materials include microstructural defects such as pores and grain boundaries.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] In addition to pores, most of the interfaces in a typical metal or ceramic object are in the form of grain boundaries, which separate tiny regions of crystalline order.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] When the size of the scattering center (or grain boundary) is reduced below the size of the wavelength of the light being scattered, the scattering no longer occurs to any significant extent.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] In the formation of polycrystalline materials (metals and ceramics) the size of the crystalline grains is determined largely by the size of the crystalline particles present in the raw material during formation (or pressing) of the object.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Moreover, the size of the grain boundaries scales directly with particle size.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Thus, a reduction of the original particle size well below the wavelength of visible light (about 1/15 of the light wavelength, or roughly 600 nm / 15 = 40 nm) eliminates much of the light scattering, resulting in a translucent or even transparent material.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Computer modeling of light transmission through translucent ceramic alumina has shown that microscopic pores trapped near grain boundaries act as primary scattering centers.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The volume fraction of porosity had to be reduced below 1% for high-quality optical transmission (99.99 percent of theoretical density).
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] This goal has been readily accomplished and amply demonstrated in laboratories and research facilities worldwide using the emerging chemical processing methods encompassed by the methods of sol-gel chemistry and nanotechnology.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Transparent ceramics have created interest in their applications for high energy lasers, transparent armor windows, nose cones for heat seeking missiles, radiation detectors for non-destructive testing, high energy physics, space exploration, security and medical imaging applications.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Large laser elements made from transparent ceramics can be produced at a relatively low cost.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] These components are free of internal stress or intrinsic birefringence, and allow relatively large doping levels or optimized custom-designed doping profiles.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] This makes ceramic laser elements particularly important for high-energy lasers.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The development of transparent panel products will have other potential advanced applications including high strength, impact-resistant materials that can be used for domestic windows and skylights.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Perhaps more important is that walls and other applications will have improved overall strength, especially for high-shear conditions found in high seismic and wind exposures.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] If the expected improvements in mechanical properties bear out, the traditional limits seen on glazing areas in today's building codes could quickly become outdated if the window area actually contributes to the shear resistance of the wall.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Currently available infrared transparent materials typically exhibit a trade-off between optical performance, mechanical strength and price.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] For example, sapphire (crystalline alumina) is very strong, but it is expensive and lacks full transparency throughout the 3–5 μm mid-infrared range.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Yttria is fully transparent from 3–5 μm, but lacks sufficient strength, hardness, and thermal shock resistance for high-performance aerospace applications.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] A combination of these two materials in the form of the yttrium aluminium garnet (YAG) is one of the top performers in the field.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] When light strikes an object, it usually has not just a single frequency (or wavelength) but many.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Objects have a tendency to selectively absorb, reflect, or transmit light of certain frequencies.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] That is, one object might reflect green light while absorbing all other frequencies of visible light.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Another object might selectively transmit blue light while absorbing all other frequencies of visible light.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The manner in which visible light interacts with an object is dependent upon the frequency of the light, the nature of the atoms in the object, and often, the nature of the electrons in the atoms of the object.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Some materials allow much of the light that falls on them to be transmitted through the material without being reflected.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Materials that allow the transmission of light waves through them are called optically transparent.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Chemically pure (undoped) window glass and clean river or spring water are prime examples of this.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Materials that do not allow the transmission of any light wave frequencies are called opaque.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Such substances may have a chemical composition which includes what are referred to as absorption centers.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Most materials are composed of materials that are selective in their absorption of light frequencies.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Thus they absorb only certain portions of the visible spectrum.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The frequencies of the spectrum which are not absorbed are either reflected back or transmitted for our physical observation.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] In the visible portion of the spectrum, this is what gives rise to color.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Absorption centers are largely responsible for the appearance of specific wavelengths of visible light all around us.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Moving from longer (0.7 μm) to shorter (0.4 μm) wavelengths: Red, orange, yellow, green, and blue (ROYGB) can all be identified by our senses in the appearance of color by the selective absorption of specific light wave frequencies (or wavelengths).
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] In electronic absorption, the frequency of the incoming light wave is at or near the energy levels of the electrons within the atoms that compose the substance.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] In this case, the electrons will absorb the energy of the light wave and increase their energy state, often moving outward from the nucleus of the atom into an outer shell or orbital.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The atoms that bind together to make the molecules of any particular substance contain a number of electrons (given by the atomic number Z in the periodic table).
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Recall that all light waves are electromagnetic in origin.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Thus they are affected strongly when coming into contact with negatively charged electrons in matter.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Most of the time, it is a combination of the above that happens to the light that hits an object.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The states in different materials vary in the range of energy that they can absorb.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Most glasses, for example, block ultraviolet (UV) light.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] What happens is the electrons in the glass absorb the energy of the photons in the UV range while ignoring the weaker energy of photons in the visible light spectrum.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] But there are also existing special glass types, like special types of borosilicate glass or quartz that are UV-permeable and thus allow a high transmission of ultraviolet light.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Thus, when a material is illuminated, individual photons of light can make the valence electrons of an atom transition to a higher electronic energy level.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The photon is destroyed in the process and the absorbed radiant energy is transformed to electric potential energy.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The primary physical mechanism for storing mechanical energy of motion in condensed matter is through heat, or thermal energy.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Thermal energy manifests itself as energy of motion.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Thus, heat is motion at the atomic and molecular levels.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The primary mode of motion in crystalline substances is vibration.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Any given atom will vibrate around some mean or average position within a crystalline structure, surrounded by its nearest neighbors.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] This vibration in two dimensions is equivalent to the oscillation of a clock's pendulum.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] It swings back and forth symmetrically about some mean or average (vertical) position.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Atomic and molecular vibrational frequencies may average on the order of 1012 cycles per second (Terahertz radiation).
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] When a light wave of a given frequency strikes a material with particles having the same or (resonant) vibrational frequencies, those particles will absorb the energy of the light wave and transform it into thermal energy of vibrational motion.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Since different atoms and molecules have different natural frequencies of vibration, they will selectively absorb different frequencies (or portions of the spectrum) of infrared light.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Reflection and transmission of light waves occur because the frequencies of the light waves do not match the natural resonant frequencies of vibration of the objects.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] When infrared light of these frequencies strikes an object, the energy is reflected or transmitted.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] If the object is transparent, then the light waves are passed on to neighboring atoms through the bulk of the material and re-emitted on the opposite side of the object.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Such frequencies of light waves are said to be transmitted.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] An object may be not transparent either because it reflects the incoming light or because it absorbs the incoming light.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Almost all solids reflect a part and absorb a part of the incoming light.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] When light falls onto a block of metal, it encounters atoms that are tightly packed in a regular lattice and a "sea of electrons" moving randomly between the atoms.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] In metals, most of these are non-bonding electrons (or free electrons) as opposed to the bonding electrons typically found in covalently bonded or ionically bonded non-metallic (insulating) solids.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] In a metallic bond, any potential bonding electrons can easily be lost by the atoms in a crystalline structure.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The effect of this delocalization is simply to exaggerate the effect of the "sea of electrons".
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] As a result of these electrons, most of the incoming light in metals is reflected back, which is why we see a shiny metal surface.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Most insulators (or dielectric materials) are held together by ionic bonds.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Thus, these materials do not have free conduction electrons, and the bonding electrons reflect only a small fraction of the incident wave.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The remaining frequencies (or wavelengths) are free to propagate (or be transmitted).
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] This class of materials includes all ceramics and glasses.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] If a dielectric material does not include light-absorbent additive molecules (pigments, dyes, colorants), it is usually transparent to the spectrum of visible light.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Color centers (or dye molecules, or "dopants") in a dielectric absorb a portion of the incoming light.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The remaining frequencies (or wavelengths) are free to be reflected or transmitted.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Most liquids and aqueous solutions are highly transparent.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] For example, water, cooking oil, rubbing alcohol, air, and natural gas are all clear.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Absence of structural defects (voids, cracks, etc.) and molecular structure of most liquids are chiefly responsible for their excellent optical transmission.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The ability of liquids to "heal" internal defects via viscous flow is one of the reasons why some fibrous materials (e.g., paper or fabric) increase their apparent transparency when wetted.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The liquid fills up numerous voids making the material more structurally homogeneous.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Light scattering in an ideal defect-free crystalline (non-metallic) solid that provides *no scattering centers* for incoming light will be due primarily to any effects of anharmonicity within the ordered lattice.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Light transmission will be highly directional due to the typical anisotropy of crystalline substances, which includes their symmetry group and Bravais lattice.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] For example, the seven different crystalline forms of quartz silica (silicon dioxide, SiO2) are all clear, transparent materials.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Optically transparent materials focus on the response of a material to incoming light waves of a range of wavelengths.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] This resonant mode of energy and data transmission via electromagnetic (light) wave propagation is relatively lossless.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] An optical fiber is a cylindrical dielectric waveguide that transmits light along its axis by the process of total internal reflection.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The fiber consists of a core surrounded by a cladding layer.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] To confine the optical signal in the core, the refractive index of the core must be greater than that of the cladding.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The refractive index is the parameter reflecting the speed of light in a material.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] (Refractive index is the ratio of the speed of light in vacuum to the speed of light in a given medium.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The refractive index of vacuum is therefore 1.) The larger the refractive index, the more slowly light travels in that medium.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Typical values for core and cladding of an optical fiber are 1.48 and 1.46, respectively.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] When light traveling in a dense medium hits a boundary at a steep angle, the light will be completely reflected.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] This effect, called total internal reflection, is used in optical fibers to confine light in the core.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Light travels along the fiber bouncing back and forth off of the boundary.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Because the light must strike the boundary with an angle greater than the critical angle, only light that enters the fiber within a certain range of angles will be propagated.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] This range of angles is called the acceptance cone of the fiber.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The size of this acceptance cone is a function of the refractive index difference between the fiber's core and cladding.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Optical waveguides are used as components in integrated optical circuits (e.g., combined with lasers or light-emitting diodes, LEDs) or as the transmission medium in local and long-haul optical communication systems.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Attenuation in fiber optics, also known as *transmission loss*, is the reduction in intensity of the light beam (or signal) with respect to distance traveled through a transmission medium.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] It is an important factor limiting the transmission of a signal across large distances.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Attenuation coefficients in fiber optics usually use units of dB/km through the medium due to the very high quality of transparency of modern optical transmission media.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] The medium is usually a fiber of silica glass that confines the incident light beam to the inside.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] In optical fibers, the main source of attenuation is scattering from molecular level irregularities, called Rayleigh scattering, due to structural disorder and compositional fluctuations of the glass structure.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] This same phenomenon is seen as one of the limiting factors in the transparency of infrared missile domes.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Further attenuation is caused by light absorbed by residual materials, such as metals or water ions, within the fiber core and inner cladding.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Light leakage due to bending, splices, connectors, or other outside forces are other factors resulting in attenuation.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] At high optical powers, scattering can also be caused by nonlinear optical processes in the fiber.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Many marine animals that float near the surface are highly transparent, giving them almost perfect camouflage.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] However, transparency is difficult for bodies made of materials that have different refractive indices from seawater.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Some marine animals such as jellyfish have gelatinous bodies, composed mainly of water; their thick mesogloea is acellular and highly transparent.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] This conveniently makes them buoyant, but it also makes them large for their muscle mass, so they cannot swim fast, making this form of camouflage a costly trade-off with mobility.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Gelatinous planktonic animals are between 50 and 90 percent transparent.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] A transparency of 50 percent is enough to make an animal invisible to a predator such as cod at a depth of 650 metres (2,130 ft); better transparency is required for invisibility in shallower water, where the light is brighter and predators can see better.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] For example, a cod can see prey that are 98 percent transparent in optimal lighting in shallow water.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Therefore, sufficient transparency for camouflage is more easily achieved in deeper waters.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] For the same reason, transparency in air is even harder to achieve, but a partial example is found in the glass frogs of the South American rain forest, which have translucent skin and pale greenish limbs.
[src:subsurface-scattering/translucency] Several Central American species of clearwing (ithomiine) butterflies and many dragonflies and allied insects also have wings which are mostly transparent, a form of crypsis that provides some protection from predators.
